metadata.name: Abstract Temples #19
metadata.description:
Giorgio de Chirico was a prominent influence on the Surrealist movement. De Chirico’s art portrays dream-like and distorted worlds that encourage viewers to explore their subconscious. 

I am fascinated by the different ways artists have found to express esoteric concepts. In particular, I am interested in how artists like Giorgio de Chirico have used light and color to create ethereal images. 

I believe that the Abstract Temples project is a perfect example of how generative art can be used to create metaphysical artwork. By invoking the visual language of the dream world, these images invite you to explore the nebulous relationship between external and internal space.

In addition to the influence of Giorgio de Chirico, I would also like to credit James Turrell as an inspiration for this project. Turrell is an artist who creates installations that play with our perception of light and space. Turrell’s work has profoundly impacted my understanding of how art can create an immersive and disorienting experience. 

Each temple room is randomly generated from a selection of 16 templates. The templates include a variety of randomized features, including the color palette, celestial objects, design variations, and other effects. They also contain a rare secret. 

This project was created with p5js. 

Features:
-16 room templates
-18 color palettes
-Celestial objects
-Secrets

metadata.name: Diversity Flow - fxhash  #8
metadata.description:
Diversity Flows – fxhash edition
An abstract expressionist collection created with code.
 
- This collection is an homage to all facets of diversity, and the importance of recognising, respecting and valuing differences. 

- The artworks were created by combining a generative flowfield algorithm with atypical shapes and forms in order to render very diverse but organic looking textures and effects. Over 50 different palettes were used, leading to very distinct-looking unique artworks.

- The algorithms were coded and run in R (The R Project for Statistical Computing, #rstats) and ported to fxhash as png images via p5js. Higher resolution images are available upon request.

Created by @1Abstract_1 (twitter handle)
https://linktr.ee/1Abstract

metadata.name: Wind Tower #7
metadata.description: Loosely inspired by Expressionist architectural sketches (e.g. Mendelsohn's Einstein Tower), this generative NFT project uses the animation of elliptical curves rotating and scaling along a central axis. A pinch of interactivity allows you to explore the artifact from different points of view.

metadata.name: Drifters #170
metadata.description:
In an undiscovered area, you've stumbled upon an unknown creature.
It looks weirdly haunting, and you're feeling a sense of unease.

You're wondering what it's doing.

It seems to move in patterns, and sometimes suddenly changes course.
Is it communicating?

(to whom?)

Setting aside your discomfort for a moment, you're realizing you could be seeing it wrong.
While the creature does look eerie and its motivations are unclear,
you realize every culture has its own appreciation of aesthetics,
and you can't help noticing there is a certain grace to this performance.

And it all makes sense.

You're witnessing uncharted explorations of elegance.

–

Append [?scale=<number>] to the url to scale the renderer.
Press [control / command + s] to save the current frame to a file.

© 2022 Monokai.

metadata.name: Omega Point #170
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Botany #212
metadata.description:
This project started as an exploration of shapes focused on the peaceful feeling that stands out in a floral composition. Amplified by the sketch and toon rendering engine allow the piece to create an infinite amount of satisfying graphic composition.

The piece is draggable and interactive, giving it a sense of tangibility that I find very satisfying. 

It comes in various schemes and styles, each feature is further described in the features section. 

If you are interested in a printed version of your mint, don't hesitate to reach out to me on Twitter so I can render a High resolution and send you a print. 
(Price may vary depending on the demands)

Made in native Webgl and Javascript, by @LodsDorian

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #17
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: contrapuntos #612
metadata.description:
Musical counterpoint is to me an abstraction of the layered, intertwining rhythms of every activity we carry on in our lives. With a global tempo typically set in days, we fit all sorts of temporal structures where our joys and fears live and play out over the span of our lives. This series is a metaphorical transposition of the musical counterpoint into a visual space, sometimes with repeating patterns, sometimes with broken structures, sometimes isolated notes / hours / souls.

Artwork by Marcelo Soria-Rodríguez, @msoriaro. Made with p5js & glsl.
